Movie: Cat on a Hot Tin Roof

Review: Reflective of our current situation, where yesterday felt like today and tomorrow will feel like today. We can only hope this time loop will end soon. Had a blast with this one.

I had a phase back in college when I would gobble up Haruki Murakami stories by the dozen. This minimalist film moves like you would while reading his novels, punctuated by jazz and character oddities (e.g., Eiko's addiction to shopping). It builds upon Murakami's usual themes of ennui and loneliness through the desolate backdrop and Ryuichi Sakamoto's stellar soundtrack. And before you know it, the film is over, questions left unanswered. This is the best adaptation of a Murakami work—yes, I liked this more than Burning—that I've seen.

Movie: Investigation of a Citizen Above Suspicion

Review: Alcazaren has my respect for making an uncomfortable film—one that makes you shift in your seat every five or so minutes, one that talks about things you only share with your significant other.

You’d think that society will do away with mob justice and groupthink more than seventy years after this movie first premiered. Sadly, it’s all the more prevalent with the advent of social media. This film just goes to highlight that it’s not the socio-cultural milieu but rather how innately vile, or gullible, or uncritical—take your pick—people can be.

Movie: Spring, Summer, Fall, Winter... and Spring

Review: This film is a showcase of everything I hate about people, especially in this age of post-truth and fake news. Infuriating in its presentation and frustrating in its reality—why don’t people get it? That this was competently made sealed the deal.

Movie: The Discreet Charm of the Bourgeoisie

Review: It feels like it's just ticking boxes to make money at the cinemas, and doesn't attempt to subvert family drama tropes. But it also hits the right emotional notes through everyone's exceptional acting.

Yikes. A partner with that many red flags isn’t worth pursuing. I can’t watch this objectively because of how much I hated the character of Catherine. What was Truffaut going for here?
Three points:1. An exercise in exploring character motivations, in the same way the three characters recreate homicides.
Generic 70s action thriller elevated by: (1) the chemistry between McQueen and MacGraw; (2) unorthodox editing choices for the action scenes; and (3) Quincy Jones’s score.
